## 4. Security Considerations 🔒

### 4A. AST Sandbox Gap in [_analyze_ast](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/module_loader/loader.py#152-187)

**Location:** [loader.py lines 180-186](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/module_loader/loader.py#L180-L186)

The AST analysis checks for dangerous calls ([exec](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/event_bus/bus.py#96-146), [eval](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/interfaces.py#107-116), [compile](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/tests/test_module_loader_coverage.py#54-61), `open`, `globals`) **but only checks `ast.Name` call nodes**. This can be **trivially bypassed** via:

```python
# Bypasses the check because it uses attribute access, not a Name node
import builtins
builtins.eval("malicious_code")  # ast.Attribute, not ast.Name

# Or via getattr (which is explicitly allowed in safe_builtins)
getattr(__builtins__, 'eval')('malicious_code')
```

> [!CAUTION]
> The `safe_builtins` whitelist in [_execute_in_sandbox](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/module_loader/loader.py#188-254) (line 204) includes [getattr](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/module_loader/loader.py#89-98) which allows runtime resolution of blocked names. An attacker could write [getattr(object, '__subclasses__')](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/module_loader/loader.py#89-98) to escape the sandbox.

**Recommendation:** The sandbox should additionally:
1. Check `ast.Attribute` nodes for forbidden method calls
2. Remove [getattr](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/module_loader/loader.py#89-98) from `safe_builtins` or wrap it with a policy-checked proxy
3. Check `ast.Call` with `ast.Attribute` func nodes (e.g., `some_obj.eval(...)`)

**Note:** In practice, modules are loaded with `builtins.__dict__` (line 415), not `safe_builtins`. The hardened sandbox is only used for the [_execute_in_sandbox](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/module_loader/loader.py#188-254) default path. The [load()](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/module_loader/loader.py#352-450) method at line 415 effectively **bypasses the sandbox entirely** by passing full builtins. This should be reviewed for production deployment.

---

### 4B. `Event.create()` Skips Signature Validation

**Location:** [types.py line 194](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/types.py#L194)

```python
signature="N/A",  # Internal events skip signature validation
```

This is by design for system events, but it means any code with access to `Event.create()` can produce unsigned events. The `EventBus.publish()` correctly rejects `"N/A"` signatures ([bus.py L79](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/event_bus/bus.py#L79)), but the [_emit_system_event](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/event_bus/bus.py#355-362) method at [line 348](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/event_bus/bus.py#L348) calls [_dispatch](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/event_bus/bus.py#326-354) directly—bypassing signature verification. This is acceptable for kernel-internal signals but should be documented.

---

## 5. Bottleneck Observation 🔄

The `EventBus._dispatch` method (line 326) executes all subscribers **synchronously and sequentially** in sorted UUID order. Per the [Phase 2 spec](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/docs/project%20plan/Project_plan.md#L16), this is **by design** ("explicit single-threaded sequential execution"). However, this creates a **linear throughput bottleneck** — a single slow subscriber blocks all subsequent handlers. The [IsolationLayer](file:///c:/Users/sergi/colony/backend/col/engine/coe-kernel/core/event_bus/bus.py#85-176) (timeout at 30s default) mitigates this but doesn't prevent latency compounding.

This aligns with finding **§1B** from the [prior findings report](file:///c:/Users/sergi/.gemini/antigravity/brain/e00aaf27-55a4-4a0d-8869-f5a4487d819f/findings_report.md.resolved).

